35/39 (89.7%) of embryos biopsied for 45yo patients were aneuploid, not 84.3% as reported in the paper.

The paper gives this regression formula to predict age vs.Â aneuploidy:

The relationship between aneuploidy and age was best predicted by a fifth order polynomial: [Percent aneuploid = 1,965 - 278.9 * Age + 16.41 * (Age)2Â - 0.4922 * (Age)3Â + 0.007451 * (Age)4 - 0.000044692 * (Age)5]. The relationship was statistically significant (P<1*10-6). This polynomial regression line is superimposed on the graph of aneuploidy vs.Â age in FigureÂ 2A.

franasiak_aneuploidy <- function(age) {
  percent_value <- 1965 -
                   278.9 * age +
                   16.41 * (age^2) -
                   0.4922 * (age^3) +
                   0.007451 * (age^4) -
                   0.000044692 * (age^5)
  return(percent_value / 100) # Convert to proportion (0-1 scale)
}

However, fig.Â 2A shows all patients 45 and older binned into a â45+â age group. Itâs not clear how they (or anyone) would draw their polynomial onto this graph.

Hereâs their data binned into the same â45+â age group, to try to recreate their figure.

t1_binned <- t1 %>%
  # group all ages 45 and above into a single group
  mutate(age_binned = ifelse(age_y >= 45, 45, age_y)) %>%
  group_by(age_binned) %>%
  summarize(aneuploidy_rate = sum(aneuploid_n) / sum(no_of_biopsies_evaluated_n))

t1_binned %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age_binned, y = aneuploidy_rate)) +
  geom_point(shape = 22, stroke = 1, size = 2, color = "#0170C4", fill = "#fefd03") +
  geom_line(color = "#0170C4") +
  # fit with 5th order polynomial
  stat_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ poly(x, 5), color = "#FD0909", se = FALSE, linewidth = .5) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(22, 45), expand = c(.02,.02), labels = c(as.character(seq(22,44)),"45+")) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent, breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.1), expand = c(0,0)) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1), xlim = c(22, 45)) +
  labs(
    caption = "Recreating Figure 2A from Franasiak et al. (2014)",
    x = "Age (years)",
    y = "Percent of Embryos Which are Aneuploid",
    tag = "2A"
  )

Exact match for chart in their paper, confirming they didnât use the (incorrectly calculated) 84.3% in plotting for the 45+ age group. But what polynomial did they actually draw on this graph?

Both of these are obviously bad models of aneuploidy in patients older than 44.

Hereâs what we would have seen in Fig. 2A without any binning of older patients.

t1 %>%

â¦ which shows at a glance that the data for their 46yo patients (4 cycles, 43 embryos?!?) is very unusual. This also makes the polynomial a worse fit to the data in the age ranges where it should be most useful, i.e.Â between 30 and 45. The extremes of the age range are where the data is most sparseâbut those points have a whole lot of leverage in a polynomial fit.

In their paper they conclude:

The prevalence of aneuploidy rose steadily from age 31 through age 43, then plateaued at approximately 85%.

That claim is just not justified by their data. Hereâs something closer to what we SHOULD have seen from a graph like this:

theme_set(theme_minimal())

alpha <- 0.05

t1_ci <- t1 %>% 
    mutate(
    aneuploidy_rate = aneuploid_n / no_of_biopsies_evaluated_n,
    ymin = qbeta(alpha / 2, aneuploid_n, no_of_biopsies_evaluated_n - aneuploid_n + 1),
    ymax = qbeta(1 - alpha / 2, aneuploid_n + 1, no_of_biopsies_evaluated_n - aneuploid_n)
  ) %>%
  # Handle edge cases where the rate is 0 or 1
  mutate(
    ymin = if_else(aneuploid_n == 0, 0, ymin),
    ymax = if_else(aneuploid_n == no_of_biopsies_evaluated_n, 1, ymax)
  )

t1_ci%>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age_y, y = aneuploidy_rate)) +
  geom_smooth(
    method = "glm",
    method.args = list(family = "binomial"),
    aes(weight = no_of_biopsies_evaluated_n),
    formula = y ~ splines::ns(x, df = 5),
    se = TRUE,
    level = 0.95,
    alpha = 0.15,
    color = "red"
  ) +
  annotate(
    geom = "text",
    x = 30,
    y = 0.5,
    label = "Binomial regression\nNatural cubic spline fit",
    color = "red",
    size = 3,
    hjust = 0
  ) +
  # Points and error bars
  geom_point(aes(size = no_of_biopsies_evaluated_n), color = "grey30") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent, breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.1)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(22, 49), minor_breaks = NULL) +
  labs(
    title = "What they might have wanted to graph instead",
    x = "Age (years)",
    y = "Aneuploidy Rate",
    tag = "2A",
    size = "Biopsies"
  )

â¦ with a wide uncertainty band (95% CI for model predictions in this case) for the top age groups where data were sparse.

Or really no need to show a model fit, can just put error bars for the measured rates:

t1_ci %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age_y, y = aneuploidy_rate)) +
  # Points and error bars
  geom_point(color = "grey30") +
  geom_errorbar(
    aes(ymin = ymin, ymax = ymax),
    width = 0.2,
    color = "grey30"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent, breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.1)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(22, 49), minor_breaks = NULL) +
  labs(
    title = "... or with no model superimposed, just error bars",
    x = "Age (years)",
    y = "Aneuploidy Rate",
    tag = "2A",
    size = "Biopsies"
  )

Overall, Iâm very surprised that this famous graph was fudged. I think it meaningfully affected their analysis and likely contributed to their overstated conclusions in the paper. Two thoughts:

  1. You canât arrive at reasonable conclusions about these data without seeing the uncertainty in the model estimates and/or sample sizes in each age bin.
  2. This is a good reminder of how many little choices are made in each data analysisâsometimes called âresearcher degrees of freedomâ. Why bin together patients 45 and older? Why not try to justify this in the text of the paper?

I think a better rephrasing of their conclusions might be:

Aneuploidy is low (<35%) in patients age 26 to 34 but rises steadily as a function of age from roughly 35% at age 35, to roughly 90% at age 45. No euploid embryos were observed in patients 47 and older. However, we cannot draw strong conclusions about aneuploidy rates in patients younger than 26 or older than 45 given how few embryos were tested from patients in those age ranges.
